e in noncontrolling interest balance from payment of dividends or other distributions by the non-wholly owned subsidiary or partially owned entity, included in the consolidation of the parent entity, to the noncontrolling interest holders.'),(1877,'MinorityInterestPeriodIncreaseDecrease',1,NULL,2,'Noncontrolling Interest, Period Increase (Decrease)','Net Increase or Decrease in balance of noncontrolling interest in the subsidiary during the reporting period.'),(1878,'MoneyMarketFundsAtCarryingValue',1,2,1,'Money Market Funds, at Carrying Value','Investment in short-term money-market instruments (such as commercial paper, banker\'s acceptances, repurchase agreements, government securities, certificates of deposit, and so forth) which are highly liquid (that is, readily convertible to known amounts of cash) and so near their maturity that they present an insignificant risk of changes in value because of changes in interest rates. Generally, only investments with original maturities of three months or less qualify as cash equivalents by definition. Original maturity means an original maturity to the entity holding the investment. For example, both a three-month US Treasury bill and a three-year Treasury note purchased three months from maturity qualify as cash equivalents. However, a Treasury note purchased three-years ago does not become a cash equivalent when its remaining maturity is three months.'),(1879,'MunicipalDebtSecuritiesAtCarryingValue',1,2,1,'Municipal Debt Securities, at Carrying Value','Bonds or similar securities issued by state, city, or local governments or the agencies operated by state, city, or local governments which are short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so near their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in value because of changes in interest rates. Generally, only investments with original maturities of three months or less qualify under that definition. Original maturity means original maturity to the entity holding the investment. For example, both a three-month US Treasury bill and a three-year Treasury note purchased three months from maturity qualify as cash equivalents. However, a Treasury note purchased three-years ago does not become a cash equivalent when its remaining maturity is three months.'),(1880,'MunicipalInvestmentAgreements',1,1,1,'Municipal Investment Agreements','Carrying value as of the balance sheet date of the obligations arising from contracts specifying rights and responsibilities of a host municipality in the structure or operation of an investment project. For example, proceeds from a revenue bond may be invested temporarily in contracts until disbursements are required for construction of a major project. There is little or no insurance risk for the entity.'),(1881,'EnergyRelatedInventoryNaturalGasLiquids',1,2,1,'Energy Related Inventory, Natural Gas Liquids','Carrying amount as of the balance sheet date of liquid hydrocarbon components recovered from natural gas.'),(1882,'NetAmountAtRiskByProductAndGuaranteeGeneralAccountValue',1,1,1,'Net Amount at Risk by Product and Guarantee, General Account Value','Value of the general accounts corresponding to the specified product, guarantee type and subset of the guarantee.'),(1883,'NetAmountAtRiskByProductAndGuaranteeNetAmountAtRisk',1,1,1,'Net Amount at Risk by Product and Guarantee, Net Amount at Risk','Net amount at risk, representing the guaranteed benefit in excess of the current account balance corresponding to the specified product, guarantee type and subset of the guarantee.'),(1884,'NetAmountAtRiskByProductAndGuaranteeSeparateAccountValue',1,1,1,'Net Amount at Risk by Product and Guarantee, Separate Account Value','Value of the separate accounts corresponding to the specified product, guarantee type and subset of the guarantee.'),(1885,'RealEstateHeldForDevelopmentAndSaleNet',1,2,1,'Real Estate Held for Development and Sale, Net','For banks, 